[asy]
unitsize(0.6inch);
pair A,B,C,D,E,M,N,P;
A = (0,3*sqrt(3));
B = (0,0);
C = (6,0);
D = (A + B)/2;
E = (B + C)/2;
M = (A + C)/2;
N = (B + C)/2;
P = extension(A,M,C,N);
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--M);
draw(C--N);
label("$A$",A,N);
label("$B$",B,SW);
label("$C$",C,SE);
label("$D$",D,W);
label("$E$",E,S);
label("$M$",M,NE);
label("$N$",N,S);
label("$P$",P,S);
[/asy]

Since $M$ is the midpoint of $AC,$ $AM = MC = \frac{1}{2} AC.$  Also, since $N$ is the midpoint of $BC,$ $CN = NB = \frac{1}{2} BC.$

By the Pythagorean Theorem on right triangle $ABC,$
\[AC = \sqrt{AB^2 + BC^2} = \sqrt{6^2 + (3 \sqrt{3})^2} = 9.\]Hence, $AM = MC = \frac{9}{2}.$

Also, $CN = NB = \frac{1}{2} BC = \frac{3 \sqrt{3}}{2}.$

Since $P$ is the intersection of the medians, $CP = \frac{2}{3} CN = \frac{2}{3} \cdot \frac{3 \sqrt{3}}{2} = \boxed{\sqrt{3}}.$

